revision.text:
'''Anal eroticism''' is erotic activity focusing on the [[anus]], and sometimes the [[rectum]]. [[Sigmund Freud]] hypothesized that the [[anal stage]] of childhood [[psychosexual development]] was marked by the predominance of anal eroticism.<ref>P. Gay, ''Freud'' (1989) p. 281-2</ref>
==Sexological== Since the mid-twentieth century, English speaking sex manuals like ''[[The Joy of Sex]]'' have acknowledged the erogenous sensitivity of the anus, and its role in love play.<ref>Alex Comfort, ''The Joy of Sex'' (1974) p. 118</ref> Its author, [[Alex Comfort]], recognised that [[anal intercourse]] was part of many heterosexual as well as homosexual relationships<ref>Alex Comfort, ''The Joy of Sex'' (1974) p. 118</ref> (as indeed had Freud at the start of the century).<ref>Sigmund Freud, ''On Sexuality'' (PFL 7) p. 64-5</ref> Comfort also stressed the importance (in the French tradition) of [[postillionage]] or [[Fingering (sexual act)#Anal fingering|anal fingering]] prior to orgasm.<ref>Alex Comfort, ''The Joy of Sex'' (1974) p. 167</ref>
Some decades after Comfort, [[Margot Anand]] explored how liberating anal eroticism might contribute to [[peak experience]] in sexual activity.<ref>Margot Anand, ''The Art of Sexual Ecstasy'' (1990) p. 1-2 and p. 336-345</ref>
==Developmental== [[D. W. Winnicott]] would speak accordingly of "the tremendous pleasure that belongs to the doing of a motion just exactly when the impulse comes...another little orgy that enriches the life of the infant".<ref>D. W. Winnicott, ''The Child, the Family, and the Outside World'' (1973) p. 43-4</ref>
Freud in his 1908 article ''Character and Anal Erotism'' argued that, through reaction formations and sublimation, anal eroticism could turn in later life into character traits such as obstinacy, orderliness and meanness.<ref>Sigmund Freud, ''On Sexuality'' (PFL 7) p. 208-15</ref> [[Sándor Ferenczi]] extended his findings to cover the sublimation of anal eroticism into aesthetic experiences such as painting and sculpture, as well as into an interest in money.<ref>Sandor Ferenczi, 'The Ontogenesis of the Interest in Money' in J. Halliday/P. Fuller eds., ''The Psychology of Gambling'' (1974) p. 264-272</ref> [[Otto Fenichel]] linked anal eroticism to feelings of [[disgust]], to [[Sadomasochism|masochism]], and to [[pornography]].<ref>Otto Fenichel, ''The Psychoanalytic Theory of Neurosis'' (1946) p. 139, 351 and 359-60</ref>
[[Julia Kristeva]] would subsequently explore anal eroticism in connection with her concept of [[abjection]].<ref>F. L. Restuccia, ''Melancholics in Love'' (2000) p. 66</ref>
